00:00:00.790 --> 00:00:04.000
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:18.230 --> 00:00:22.060
&gt;&gt; So hello, good afternoon,
my name is Tracy North.

00:00:22.060 --> 00:00:25.020
I am a reference librarian
in the Hispanic Division

00:00:25.020 --> 00:00:27.710
and Social Sciences
Editor of the "Handbook

00:00:27.710 --> 00:00:31.400
of Latin American Studies",
an annotated guide

00:00:31.400 --> 00:00:33.920
to scholarly publications
about Latin America

00:00:33.920 --> 00:00:37.210
that has been published since 1936

00:00:37.210 --> 00:00:40.700
and includes quite a few
references to baseball I might add.

00:00:40.700 --> 00:00:44.800 position:56%
So, on behalf of the Library of
Congress I am excited to welcome you

00:00:44.800 --> 00:00:48.640
to today's talk by journalist
and author Cesar Brioso

00:00:48.640 --> 00:00:51.980
about his new book "Havana
Hardball: Spring Training,

00:00:51.980 --> 00:00:54.850
Jackie Robinson and
the Cuban League".

00:00:54.850 --> 00:00:56.990
Do you know how many
Cubans are playing

00:00:56.990 --> 00:00:58.410
in Major League Baseball today?

00:00:58.410 --> 00:01:04.420
Do you know who was the first
Cuban to play in the MLB and when?

00:01:04.420 --> 00:01:08.450
Have you heard of New York
Yankees' closer Aroldis Chapman

00:01:08.450 --> 00:01:11.870
who was traded from the Reds
last year and is rumored to be

00:01:11.870 --> 00:01:14.260
on the verge of getting
traded again?

00:01:14.260 --> 00:01:17.250
He had a great night against my
Baltimore Orioles the other night,

00:01:17.250 --> 00:01:20.900
routinely throwing
100-mile-an-hour fastballs.

00:01:20.900 --> 00:01:24.460
Today, you will learn about some
of the historical foundations

00:01:24.460 --> 00:01:29.660
of Cuban baseball on the island
with a focus on 1946 and 1947.

00:01:29.660 --> 00:01:33.880
You'll learn about the rivalry
between the Almendares and Habana,

00:01:33.880 --> 00:01:36.220
similar to rivalries
between the New York Yankees

00:01:36.220 --> 00:01:39.620
and the Brooklyn Dodgers
of Jackie Robinson's era

00:01:39.620 --> 00:01:43.820
or there is Boca Juniors versus
River Plate in Argentine soccer,

00:01:43.820 --> 00:01:48.830
Barcelona versus Real Madrid
in Spain, Borg versus McEnroe,

00:01:48.830 --> 00:01:51.320
Chrissie versus Martina
in tennis in the 80s.

00:01:51.320 --> 00:01:53.060
You get the idea.

00:01:53.060 --> 00:01:54.440
As you may know the Library

00:01:54.440 --> 00:01:58.030
of Congress now holds the
Jackie Robinson Papers.

00:01:58.030 --> 00:01:59.990 position:56%
Preparing for his major league debut

00:01:59.990 --> 00:02:03.750
with the Brooklyn Dodgers Robinson
participated in spring training

00:02:03.750 --> 00:02:06.800
with the team in Cuba in 1947.

00:02:06.800 --> 00:02:10.500
The idea was that he would be able
to avoid the attention of the press

00:02:10.500 --> 00:02:12.790
and unsupportive fans in Florida,

00:02:12.790 --> 00:02:15.880
the team's usual spring
training location.

00:02:15.880 --> 00:02:20.770
At that time remember we're talking
about pre-revolutionary Cuba.

00:02:20.770 --> 00:02:24.980
Robinson was not the first or only
American in Cuba during that time.

00:02:24.980 --> 00:02:28.640
Think Hemingway whose
birthday is today by the way,

00:02:28.640 --> 00:02:33.030
Sinatra, Meyer Lansky et cetera.

00:02:33.030 --> 00:02:36.470
These are just some of the topics
that you'll hear more about today

00:02:36.470 --> 00:02:40.740
from Cesar Brioso, a digital
producer for USA Today's sports

00:02:40.740 --> 00:02:44.960
where he served as baseball
editor from 2003 to 2004.

00:02:44.960 --> 00:02:46.660
Cesar has been a writer or editor

00:02:46.660 --> 00:02:49.930
at several other papers
including The Miami Herald,

00:02:49.930 --> 00:02:53.180
South Florida Sun Sentinel
and Tampa Tribune.

00:02:53.180 --> 00:02:55.110
He's a member of the Society

00:02:55.110 --> 00:02:58.420
for American Baseball Research
