00:02:58.420 --> 00:03:01.990
coming up next week in
Florida and he blogs

00:03:01.990 --> 00:03:06.090
about Cuban baseball
history at cubanbaseball,

00:03:06.090 --> 00:03:08.700
spelled in Spanish, dot.com.

00:03:08.700 --> 00:03:12.050
Now I'd like to turn the
program over to Cesar.

00:03:12.050 --> 00:03:13.880
&gt;&gt; Thank you, good afternoon.

00:03:13.880 --> 00:03:16.820
Thank you all for coming and thank
you to the Library of Congress

00:03:16.820 --> 00:03:21.380
for letting me talk about
my book "Havana Hardball".

00:03:21.380 --> 00:03:25.590
And so broadly, the book
is about baseball in Cuba

00:03:25.590 --> 00:03:28.060
in the mid to late 1940s.

00:03:28.060 --> 00:03:32.330
It's a pivotal time in baseball
history when Cuba finds itself

00:03:32.330 --> 00:03:34.420
at the epicenter of
events that are going

00:03:34.420 --> 00:03:38.460
to impact not just the Cuban League
but also other Latin leagues,

00:03:38.460 --> 00:03:42.060
Major League Baseball and the
Negro Leagues for years to come.

00:03:42.060 --> 00:03:46.270
I chose to focus on this
particular time period at least

00:03:46.270 --> 00:03:48.410
in part because of my father.

00:03:48.410 --> 00:03:50.100
You'll see a photo of him here.

00:03:50.100 --> 00:03:53.920
That's him as a kid in Cuba
with one of his uncles.

00:03:53.920 --> 00:03:57.730
He, the hat he's wearing
is Almendares, one of the.

00:03:57.730 --> 00:03:59.690
That's his favorite team,
one of the four teams

00:03:59.690 --> 00:04:02.530
in the Cuban League at that time.

00:04:02.530 --> 00:04:04.850
Like when I was a kid my dad
would tell me all these stories

00:04:04.850 --> 00:04:09.170
about American ball players who
would come to Cuba every winter

00:04:09.170 --> 00:04:11.890
to play baseball and you're
seeing some of the photos up here.

00:04:11.890 --> 00:04:16.770
You know familiar names, Tommy
Lasorda who became a Hall

00:04:16.770 --> 00:04:20.430
of Fame manager with the
Dodgers, future Hall of Famers

00:04:20.430 --> 00:04:24.690
from the Negro League like
Monte Irvin and Ray Dandridge

00:04:24.690 --> 00:04:28.090
and as you're seeing right
here a guy named Kevin Connors

00:04:28.090 --> 00:04:31.380
who you would be more familiar
with the name Chuck Connors

00:04:31.380 --> 00:04:33.430
from the, Hollywood actor.

00:04:33.430 --> 00:04:35.580
He was, before he became
a Hollywood actor

00:04:35.580 --> 00:04:39.660
in "The Rifleman" he was a player
in the Dodgers Farm System.

00:04:39.660 --> 00:04:43.400
So I'd hear all these stories
as I was a kid and then as,

00:04:43.400 --> 00:04:46.670
once I became a sports writer
working in Florida I started

00:04:46.670 --> 00:04:50.880 position:56%
to find a lot of these guys
retired and in, throughout the state

00:04:50.880 --> 00:04:54.130
and I would interview them for
stories for the various papers

00:04:54.130 --> 00:04:58.010
that I worked for at the
time and started building,

00:04:58.010 --> 00:04:59.690
collecting all these
interviews with the idea

00:04:59.690 --> 00:05:01.800
of eventually, someday
writing a book.

00:05:01.800 --> 00:05:08.720
And when I finally got a
publisher, sort of the last stage

00:05:08.720 --> 00:05:14.050
of my research was the Library
of Congress, was very helpful.

00:05:14.050 --> 00:05:18.230
They have a great collection of
Cuban newspapers on microfilm.

00:05:18.230 --> 00:05:21.690 position:56%
I was able to access those, not just
here but what was really helpful was

00:05:21.690 --> 00:05:26.760
that the Library of Congress was
gracious enough to allow them

00:05:26.760 --> 00:05:31.960 position:56%
to be sent to Fairfax County Library
where I live which made research

00:05:31.960 --> 00:05:36.140
so much easier not having to come
into the District multiple times

00:05:36.140 --> 00:05:38.410
to be able to look
through all those articles.

00:05:38.410 --> 00:05:41.250
That's broadly what
the book is about.

00:05:41.250 --> 00:05:47.740
Specifically it focuses on the
1946-47 Cuban League season.

00:05:47.740 --> 00:05:50.040
That is what is still
considered kind

00:05:50.040 --> 00:05:52.290
of the greatest finish
in league history.

00:05:52.290 --> 00:05:56.780
It came down to a three-game series
between Almandares and Habana,

00:05:56.780 --> 00:05:58.530
the eternal rivals
as they were called.

00:05:58.530 --> 00:06:02.830
Both teams had been in the Cuban
League since its formation in 1878,

00:06:02.830 --> 00:06:06.900 position:56%
just two years after the start of
the National League here in the U.S.

00:06:06.900 --> 00:06:10.360 position:56%
And as the three games, the decisive
three-game series was being played

00:06:10.360 --> 00:06:14.670
out the Dodgers arrived for
spring training in Havana

00:06:14.670 --> 00:06:19.130
and with them came their Triple
AAA Farm Team, the Montreal Royals

00:06:19.130 --> 00:06:23.570
which included not only Jackie
Robinson but also Roy Campanella,

00:06:23.570 --> 00:06:25.660
Don Newcombe and Roy Partlow.

00:06:25.660 --> 00:06:30.880
And so the book alternates
between those two storylines

00:06:30.880 --> 00:06:34.770
in alternating chapters and they
play out against the backdrop

00:06:34.770 --> 00:06:38.630
of the Mexican League trying
to get major league players

00:06:38.630 --> 00:06:42.680
to jump their contracts to
play in their summer league.

00:06:42.680 --> 00:06:50.080
And why that matters
is because they,

00:06:50.080 --> 00:06:53.880 position:56%
them trying to get all these players
to jump, and in fact they got

00:06:53.880 --> 00:06:56.430
like 20-something players
to jump their contracts.

00:06:56.430 --> 00:06:59.440
Commissioner Happy Chandler
declared that any player

00:06:59.440 --> 00:07:01.890
who jumped their contracts
would be ineligible

00:07:01.890 --> 00:07:04.000
to play Major League Baseball
and organized baseball

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:06.800
for at least five years, and
even then there was no guarantee

00:07:06.800 --> 00:07:08.510
that they'd be allowed back.

00:07:08.510 --> 00:07:11.710 position:56%
And that matters to the Cuban League
because so many players played

00:07:11.710 --> 00:07:15.840 position:56%
in the Cuban League of those jumpers
and Cuban players also played

00:07:15.840 --> 00:07:20.570 position:56%
in Mexico or managed or coached in
Mexico so Chandler had also declared

00:07:20.570 --> 00:07:21.870
that anyone who played with

00:07:21.870 --> 00:07:25.530
or against those jumpers
would also be ineligible

00:07:25.530 --> 00:07:27.120
to play in organized baseball.

00:07:27.120 --> 00:07:31.800
So in essence the Cuban League
which had enjoyed great relations

00:07:31.800 --> 00:07:35.640
with Major League Baseball and had
players from the majors playing

00:07:35.640 --> 00:07:36.940
in Cuba either in the league

00:07:36.940 --> 00:07:41.770
or barnstorming really
throughout the 20th century,

00:07:41.770 --> 00:07:43.070
they were suddenly a rogue league

00:07:43.070 --> 00:07:47.410
and their players were rogue
players, just by playing

00:07:47.410 --> 00:07:50.340
in the league were, their careers,

00:07:50.340 --> 00:07:55.120
futures in organized
baseball were threatened.

00:07:55.120 --> 00:07:59.410
So, and the book explores sort
of how all these conflicts came

00:07:59.410 --> 00:08:04.090
into being, how they got resolved
and what happens going forward.

00:08:04.090 --> 00:08:07.300
So, with that I think
I'll just open it up.

00:08:07.300 --> 00:08:10.510
I'd prefer to have, it be more of a
conversation than me just standing

00:08:10.510 --> 00:08:12.910
up here, kind of telling
you about the book

00:08:12.910 --> 00:08:14.710
so hopefully you have
some interesting questions

00:08:14.710 --> 00:08:16.620 position:56%
and I'll be glad to answer them now.

00:08:16.620 --> 00:08:17.920
Yes?

00:08:17.920 --> 00:08:19.220
&gt;&gt; Since it was raised
in the introduction,

00:08:19.220 --> 00:08:22.770
who was the first Cuban in the
Major League Baseball in America?

00:08:22.770 --> 00:08:26.070
&gt;&gt; The very first Cuban in
the majors was Esteban Bellan

00:08:26.070 --> 00:08:29.210
with the Detroit Haymakers in, I'm
trying to remember now off the top

00:08:29.210 --> 00:08:31.110
of my head, 1870 something.

00:08:31.110 --> 00:08:35.120
But in terms of the modern era
since 1900 there were a pair

00:08:35.120 --> 00:08:39.750
of Cuban players signed by
the Cincinnati Reds in 1911,

00:08:39.750 --> 00:08:43.360
Rafael Almeida and Armando Marsans.

00:08:43.360 --> 00:08:48.990
So they joined in, like I said 1911
and when they were first signed

00:08:48.990 --> 00:08:51.340
and were playing in the
minors there was this.

00:08:51.340 --> 00:08:53.860
In my research I found
this sort of rushed by,

00:08:53.860 --> 00:09:01.420
newspapers to assure baseball fans
that they were in fact, white,

00:09:01.420 --> 00:09:05.310
really kind of amazing words used.

00:09:05.310 --> 00:09:09.150
One, I believe the Cincinnati
Enquirer, if I remember correctly,

00:09:09.150 --> 00:09:12.660
referred to them as the
two, two purest bars

00:09:12.660 --> 00:09:17.130
of Castilian soap ever
sailed to these shores.

00:09:17.130 --> 00:09:20.320
And there were all kinds
of, I mean that's kind

00:09:20.320 --> 00:09:23.310
of how they were described.

00:09:23.310 --> 00:09:28.210
Multiple newspaper accounts again
assuring white major league fans

00:09:28.210 --> 00:09:30.280
that no, they're not black.

00:09:30.280 --> 00:09:34.830
They're Cuban or they're of
you know European ancestry.

00:09:34.830 --> 00:09:39.800
One referred to them as having
no ignoble African blood

00:09:39.800 --> 00:09:44.790
so all these references in the 19,
the teens, trying to describe them

00:09:44.790 --> 00:09:47.760
and assure fans they weren't black.

00:09:50.870 --> 00:09:52.170
Yes? I'm sorry.

00:09:52.170 --> 00:09:54.420
&gt;&gt; So what was the
racial situation in Cuba

00:09:54.420 --> 00:09:57.430 position:56%
in that summer that Jackie Robinson?

00:09:57.430 --> 00:09:59.550
Were there any problems there?

00:09:59.550 --> 00:10:02.340
&gt;&gt; No, not at all, in fact the
Cuban League had been integrated

00:10:02.340 --> 00:10:05.620
since 1900 so they were far ahead

00:10:05.620 --> 00:10:08.920
of integration here
in the major leagues.

00:10:08.920 --> 00:10:13.420
In fact that's one of the
reasons why Branch Rickey chose

00:10:13.420 --> 00:10:16.810
to move the Dodgers' spring
training from Daytona Beach.

00:10:16.810 --> 00:10:19.100
That's where they trained
in 1946, to Havana.

00:10:19.100 --> 00:10:20.400
They had been.

00:10:20.400 --> 00:10:21.700
They were familiar with Havana.

00:10:21.700 --> 00:10:24.260
They had trained there
in 1941 and 1942

00:10:24.260 --> 00:10:29.000
and in '46 Robinson's first year
with the Royals they had a bunch

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:31.870
of issues trying to play games.

00:10:31.870 --> 00:10:36.290
When the Royals would go to play a
minor league spring training game

00:10:36.290 --> 00:10:39.360
they might find that the
stadium was padlocked

00:10:39.360 --> 00:10:43.620
or that there was a sudden lighting
malfunction so they couldn't play.

00:10:43.620 --> 00:10:49.140 position:56%
In one instance a police officer
informed that there was an ordinance

00:10:49.140 --> 00:10:52.760
where black and white players could
not share the same baseball field.

00:10:52.760 --> 00:10:57.150
So they encountered all
these issues in 1946

00:10:57.150 --> 00:11:02.580
so when Branch Rickey was planning
to make sure that that was the,

00:11:02.580 --> 00:11:03.940
in '47, that that was the year

00:11:03.940 --> 00:11:07.410
that he would elevate
Robinson to the Dodgers.

00:11:07.410 --> 00:11:09.410
That's why he chose
to move to Havana

00:11:09.410 --> 00:11:14.130
because of the better
racial climate certainly

00:11:14.130 --> 00:11:17.830
in baseball and in society as well.

00:11:17.830 --> 00:11:19.130
There were.

00:11:19.130 --> 00:11:22.390
It's not to say that there's
no racism or no issues in Cuba

00:11:22.390 --> 00:11:24.880
but it certainly was
not the codified racism

00:11:24.880 --> 00:11:30.060
that you had here especially
in Florida with Jim Crow laws.

00:11:31.380 --> 00:11:34.500
&gt;&gt; The ownership of the Cuban
League teams at that time,

00:11:34.500 --> 00:11:40.920 position:56%
was it pretty much all indigenous
ownership or was there any influence

00:11:40.920 --> 00:11:43.760
of American owners or
investors down there?

00:11:43.760 --> 00:11:46.750
&gt;&gt; No, it was pretty
much owned by Cubans.

00:11:46.750 --> 00:11:53.250 position:56%
In fact one of the sort of, baseball
legends Miguel Angel Gonzalez,

00:11:53.250 --> 00:11:54.550
he played.

00:11:54.550 --> 00:11:58.490
He was also one of the early
Cuban players in the majors.

00:11:58.490 --> 00:12:02.580
He played in 1920s-30s.

00:12:02.580 --> 00:12:07.110
He played with the Cardinals,
Giants, White Sox, several teams.

00:12:07.110 --> 00:12:09.990
He was a catcher and
played with Habana most

00:12:09.990 --> 00:12:11.290
of his career as a player.

00:12:11.290 --> 00:12:14.260
He eventually became manager
of Habana, saved enough money

00:12:14.260 --> 00:12:17.250
to become a part-owner and
eventually owned the entire team.

00:12:17.250 --> 00:12:19.330
And that was pretty typical.

00:12:19.330 --> 00:12:22.350
It was either individual,
Cuban individuals or a group

00:12:22.350 --> 00:12:24.320
of Cubans who owned each team.

00:12:24.320 --> 00:12:30.290 position:56%
Almendares was owned by a group that
had ties to the Vedado Tennis Club

00:12:30.290 --> 00:12:37.300 position:56%
which was a social club for affluent
Cubans so that was pretty typical

00:12:37.300 --> 00:12:42.450
of the teams in the Cuban League.

00:12:42.450 --> 00:12:43.750
Yes?

00:12:43.750 --> 00:12:46.400
&gt;&gt; Would you mind speaking sort
of generally about baseball

00:12:46.400 --> 00:12:51.510
in Latin America and then
baseball introduction to Cuba?

00:12:51.510 --> 00:12:54.020
How did it go from being this
game that we've all heard

00:12:54.020 --> 00:12:57.910
about having its roots in
America and now we're talking

00:12:57.910 --> 00:13:00.220
about Latin America and Cuba so?

00:13:00.220 --> 00:13:06.990
&gt;&gt; Well, baseball was introduced
in Cuba around, in the 1860s.

00:13:06.990 --> 00:13:10.880
Students who, Cuban students who
went to the United States to study

00:13:10.880 --> 00:13:14.930
in college brought the game back
to Cuba in that time period.

00:13:14.930 --> 00:13:18.710
It also kind of was helped
spread by the presence

00:13:18.710 --> 00:13:21.930
of U.S. military in Cuba.

00:13:21.930 --> 00:13:28.190
I've seen dozens of photos of U.S.
Navy teams playing in Guantanamo

00:13:28.190 --> 00:13:30.990
in the early part of
the 20th century.

00:13:30.990 --> 00:13:34.500 position:56%
So, that's where it was first
introduced and it really became sort

00:13:34.500 --> 00:13:36.380
of engrained in the Cuban
culture with the fight

00:13:36.380 --> 00:13:39.510
for independence against Spain.

00:13:39.510 --> 00:13:44.500
It became, sort of, one way
of expressing their rejection

00:13:44.500 --> 00:13:50.280
of Spanish rule, choosing baseball
over bullfighting for example.

00:13:50.280 --> 00:13:56.420 position:56%
And it also became engrained as part
of that with the exiled communities

00:13:56.420 --> 00:13:59.410
in Key West, Ybor City in Tampa.

00:13:59.410 --> 00:14:03.490
They would form their own social
clubs here in the United States

00:14:03.490 --> 00:14:07.250
and they would put on baseball
games and some of the proceeds

00:14:07.250 --> 00:14:10.550
from those games would be sent
back to Cuba to fight the,

00:14:10.550 --> 00:14:12.720
for the fight for independence.

00:14:12.720 --> 00:14:18.020
So in the late 1800s it really
started to become entrenched

00:14:18.020 --> 00:14:21.700
and be part of Cuban culture,
what it means to be Cuban.

00:14:21.700 --> 00:14:24.610
And then Cuba really
became sort of the apostles

00:14:24.610 --> 00:14:27.270
of baseball throughout
the Caribbean,

00:14:27.270 --> 00:14:31.500
spreading it to other countries.

00:14:31.500 --> 00:14:36.110 position:56%
There were some people who left
Cuba to, you know because of the war

00:14:36.110 --> 00:14:39.130
to places like Mexico and the
Dominican Republic for safety

00:14:39.130 --> 00:14:42.560
and kind of brought the game
there with them then and it built

00:14:42.560 --> 00:14:44.360
up through that, that way.

00:14:44.360 --> 00:14:49.780
&gt;&gt; Can you take that one step
further to then integrating

00:14:49.780 --> 00:14:51.400
into Major League Baseball
in the U.S.?

00:14:51.400 --> 00:14:56.370
I guess it was Cubans a lot first
and then when that ended other,

00:14:56.370 --> 00:14:59.230
players from other countries
started to come more?

00:14:59.230 --> 00:15:03.630
&gt;&gt; Right, before the Castro
